{"cursor":"5148","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party native_name = Magyar Szocialista\n| MunkÃ¡spÃ¡rt logo = leader1_title = First leader leader1_name = JÃ¡nos KÃ¡dÃ¡r\n| leader2_title = Last leader leader2_name = RezsÅ Nyers foundation = 25\n| October 1956 dissolution = 7 October 1989 membership = youth_wing = Hungarian\n| Young Communist League international = [[Comecon]] predecessor = Hungarian\n| Working People's Party successor = Hungarian Socialist Party, Hungarian\n| Communist Workers' Party european = colors = Red, white, green (Colours of\n| the Hungarian flag) colorcode = red website = headquarters = Budapest,\n| People's Republic of Hungary ideology = Communism, MarxismâLeninism, KÃ¡dÃ¡rism country = Hungary\n}} The 'Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party' (, MSzMP) was the ruling\nMarxistâLeninist party of Hungary between 1956 and 1989. It was organised from\nelements of the Hungarian Working People's Party during the Hungarian Revolution\nof 1956, with JÃ¡nos KÃ¡dÃ¡r as general secretary.\n\nThe party initially supported the revolution, but turned against Imre Nagy's\ngovernment after he denounced the Warsaw Pact. The party formed a 'Revolutionary\nPeasant-Worker Government' that took over the country, with Soviet support, on 4\nNovember 1956. Gradually, however, the KÃ¡dÃ¡r regime instituted goulash\nCommunism, a somewhat more humane way of governing than had prevailed under\nMÃ¡tyÃ¡s RÃ¡kosi. Under KÃ¡dÃ¡r's mantra of \"he who is not against us is with us,\"\nHungarians generally had more freedom than their Eastern Bloc counterparts to go\nabout their daily lives. The government also gave limited freedom to the\nworkings of the market. While the MSzMP regime was not nearly as repressive as\nits Warsaw Pact counterparts, at bottom it was still authoritarian. It retained\na monopoly of political power, and subjected the media to censorship that was\nfairly onerous by Western standards. The National Assembly, like its\ncounterparts in the rest of the Soviet bloc, did little more than rubber-stamp\ndecisions already made by the MSzMP.\n\nKÃ¡dÃ¡r retired on 22 May 1988 and was succeeded by Prime Minister KÃ¡roly GrÃ³sz.\nHowever, GrÃ³sz soon found himself eclipsed by a group of radical reformers who\nfavored establishing a market economy. On 28 January 1989, young Politburo\nmember and minister of state Imre Pozsgay announced during an interview with the\nradio program 168 Hours that the Poliburo`s historical sub-committee regarded\nthe events of 1956 as a 'people's uprising'. This announcement, not approved in\nadvance by the Politburo, provoked and catalyzed various developments within the\nparty, and brought about sudden and ever-escalating changes that led to the\nending of Communism in Hungary and the dissolution of the MSzMP. http://www-\n.coldwar.hu/html/en/publications/roundtable_kalmar.html\n\nBy the summer of 1989, the party's radical reformers, led by Prime Minister\nMiklÃ³s NÃ©meth, Foreign Minister Gyula Horn, RezsÅ Nyers and Pozsgay, had gained\ncontrol of the party. On 26 June 1989, the Politburo was replaced by a four-man\ncollective presidency chaired by Nyers. Although GrÃ³sz remained general\nsecretary, Nyers now outranked him. On 7 October 1989 the MSzMP was dissolved\nand refounded as the Hungarian Socialist Party, a Western-style social\ndemocratic party. A small group of MSzMP members led by GrÃ³sz opposed this move,\nand went on to form the Hungarian Communist Workers' Party on 17 December 1989.\n","linknr":267,"url":"Hungarian_Socialist_Workers'_Party","recorded":1375082515,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hungarian_Socialist_Workers%27_Party&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hungarian_Socialist_Workers%27_Party&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:R